The Tipping Point - How Little Things Can Make a Big Difference by Malcolm Gladwell


Gladwell defines a tipping point as &quot;the moment of critical mass, the threshold, the boiling point.&quot;  The book seeks to explain and describe the &quot;mysterious&quot; sociological changes that mark everyday life. As Gladwell states, &quot;Ideas and products and messages and behaviors spread like viruses do.&quot; The examples of such changes in his book include the rise in popularity and sales of Hush Puppies shoes in the mid-1990s and the precipitous drop in the New York City crime rate after 1990. &lt;a href=&quot;
